<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,353,368,394]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">Bombus flavidus</emphasis>
Eversmann, 1852
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="55" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,438,679]" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">
<taxonomicName box="[151,341,438,463]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavidus">
<emphasis box="[151,341,438,463]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">Bombus flavidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a boreo-alpine species, distributed in the north of the Eurasian continent, Scandinavia and Siberia, where the nominal subspecies spreads. It is the social parasite of 
<taxonomicName box="[982,1106,474,499]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jonellus">
<emphasis box="[982,999,476,499]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1014,1106,474,499]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">jonellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[1106,1110,474,499]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">,</emphasis>
but in the Pyrenees it shows preference for 
<taxonomicName box="[315,459,511,534]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ranunculaceae" genus="Ranunculus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="14" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pyrenaeus">
<emphasis box="[315,459,511,534]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">B. pyrenaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and secondarily by 
<taxonomicName box="[683,825,510,535]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monticola">
<emphasis box="[683,825,510,535]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">B. monticola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Loken" box="[839,978,510,535]" pageId="14" pageNumber="55" refString="Loken, A. (1984) Scandinavian species of the genus Psithyrus Lepeletier (Hymenoptera: Apidae). Entomologica Scandinavica Supplement, 23, 16438," type="journal article" year="1984">Løken 1984</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Rasmont" box="[989,1155,511,535]" pageId="14" pageNumber="55" refString="Rasmont, P. (1988) Monographie ecologique et zoogeographique des Bourdons de France et de Belgique (Hymenoptera, Apidae, Bombinae). Faculte des Sciences agronomiques de L´Etat, Gembloux, 310 pp." type="book" year="1988">Rasmont 1988</bibRefCitation>
). There is a double threat to 
<taxonomicName box="[180,300,546,571]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavidus">
<emphasis box="[180,300,546,571]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">B. flavidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
since the two main host species have small and declining populations (
<tableCitation box="[1097,1185,546,571]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,239,152,175]" captionTargetBox="[159,1394,332,1883]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="TABLE 2. Bumblebee species and subspecies collected in the Pyrenees and IUCN category ranks (from Spain: Verdú &amp; Galante (2006), Verdú et al. (2011) and from Europe: Rasmont et al. (2015): Not Evaluated, NE; Endangered, EN; Vulnerable, VU; Data Deficient, DD; Least Concern, LC) of the extant bumblebee species and subspecies in the Pyrenees. The number of individuals sampled between 2006 and 2015 is indicated. In rare species and those with relevant records, the number of individuals known from historical literature or collections is included in brackets." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/BDBE6627FF98FFBFFF3CFF45FADEFED5" pageId="14" pageNumber="55" tableUuid="BDBE6627FF98FFBFFF3CFF45FADEFED5">Table 2</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,438,679]" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">
It was assessed as Least Concern in the 
<collectionCode box="[681,749,583,607]" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">IUCN</collectionCode>
Red List of European Bees (Rasmont 
<emphasis box="[1212,1273,582,607]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">et al.</emphasis>
2015) and as Endangered (EN) in the 
<collectionCode box="[428,496,619,643]" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">IUCN</collectionCode>
Spanish Red List (Ornosa &amp; Torres 2009), where it is locally less abundant (
<tableCitation captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,239,152,175]" captionTargetBox="[159,1394,332,1883]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="TABLE 2. Bumblebee species and subspecies collected in the Pyrenees and IUCN category ranks (from Spain: Verdú &amp; Galante (2006), Verdú et al. (2011) and from Europe: Rasmont et al. (2015): Not Evaluated, NE; Endangered, EN; Vulnerable, VU; Data Deficient, DD; Least Concern, LC) of the extant bumblebee species and subspecies in the Pyrenees. The number of individuals sampled between 2006 and 2015 is indicated. In rare species and those with relevant records, the number of individuals known from historical literature or collections is included in brackets." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/BDBE6627FF98FFBFFF3CFF45FADEFED5" pageId="14" pageNumber="55" tableUuid="BDBE6627FF98FFBFFF3CFF45FADEFED5">Table 2</tableCitation>
). In the Pyrenean fauna, it is represented by a unique subspecies:
